---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CTASection from '../components/react/CTASection';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About | Ángel Luis Catalán"
  description="Professional background and engineering approach of Ángel Luis Catalán, Senior Cloud Engineer based in Madrid."
>

  <!-- ── Header ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="border-b border-slate-800 py-24" style="background-color: #0a0f1e;">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <span class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-blue-400">
        About
      </span>
      <h1 class="mt-3 text-3xl font-bold text-white sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl leading-tight">
        Ángel Luis Catalán
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-lg font-medium text-slate-300">
        Senior Cloud Engineer · Azure · Terraform · DevOps
      </p>
      <p class="mt-1 font-mono text-sm text-slate-500">Madrid, Spain · Kyndryl</p>

      <p class="mt-8 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
        I've spent the last decade working in enterprise environments where reliability,
        operational discipline and scale aren't optional requirements — they're the baseline.
        That background shapes how I think about cloud infrastructure: not as a collection
        of services to provision, but as a platform that needs to be designed, maintained and evolved.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Professional journey ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="border-b border-slate-800 py-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <span class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-blue-400">
        Background
      </span>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold text-white sm:text-3xl">
        Professional journey
      </h2>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
        <p>
          My career started in workload automation — managing enterprise scheduling platforms
          across critical financial and industrial environments. That meant operating systems
          that ran continuously, where failures had real consequences and where documentation,
          runbooks and structured incident response were non-negotiable. Those habits didn't
          go away when I moved into cloud.
        </p>
        <p>
          Over time, the scope expanded. I moved from managing pipelines and jobs to designing
          the infrastructure those pipelines run on. First deeper into Linux systems, scripting
          and database administration. Then into cloud: Azure infrastructure, networking,
          security, CI/CD, and eventually full platform engineering with Terraform at the centre.
        </p>
        <p>
          The current role at Kyndryl is where those threads come together. Azure infrastructure
          design and deployment, Terraform automation, DevOps integration, Snowflake provisioning,
          Couchbase Capella deployment via IaC — all within enterprise delivery constraints.
          Not proof-of-concept work. Production platforms for real clients.
        </p>
        <p>
          The trajectory is clear: from operational discipline toward cloud architecture and
          platform design. The hands-on foundation makes the architectural thinking more
          grounded — I don't propose solutions I haven't had to operate.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Engineering approach ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="border-b border-slate-800 py-20" style="background-color: #080d1a;">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <span class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-blue-400">
        Engineering approach
      </span>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold text-white sm:text-3xl">
        How I approach cloud engineering
      </h2>

      <div class="mt-10 space-y-10">

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white">Infrastructure as code is not optional</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
            Manual provisioning doesn't scale and doesn't survive team changes. Every environment
            I work on gets a Terraform codebase — with remote state, consistent naming, modular
            structure and CI/CD integration from the start. The discipline of writing infrastructure
            as code forces better design decisions: you can't hide complexity in a portal click.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white">Automation with purpose, not automation for its own sake</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
            Not every process needs to be automated, but every process that runs regularly does.
            The goal is reducing toil and error surface, not building automation that itself becomes
            a maintenance burden. I approach pipelines the same way: each step should have a clear
            reason, a clear failure mode and a clear owner.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white">Security and networking are first-class concerns</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
            Azure networking is where a lot of enterprise complexity lives: hub-spoke topologies,
            NSG rule design, Private Endpoints, DNS resolution across peered networks, firewall
            policy hierarchies. I've debugged enough connectivity issues to treat network design
            as something that must be right from day one — retrofitting security onto an existing
            platform is significantly harder than designing it in.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white">Operational clarity over clever design</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
            Infrastructure that is hard to understand is infrastructure that will fail at the
            worst moment. Clear resource naming, consistent tagging, readable Terraform modules,
            documented runbooks — these aren't polish. They're part of the engineering. An on-call
            engineer dealing with an incident at 3am should be able to understand the platform
            without asking questions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white">Platform thinking over one-off deployments</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
            The most valuable infrastructure work is not delivering a single environment — it's
            building the patterns and tooling that make every subsequent environment cheaper,
            faster and more consistent to deliver. Reusable Terraform modules, standardised
            pipeline templates, shared naming conventions and governance guardrails are how
            you scale platform operations without scaling the team proportionally.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Real environments ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="border-b border-slate-800 py-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <span class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-blue-400">
        Experience
      </span>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold text-white sm:text-3xl">
        Working in real environments
      </h2>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
        <p>
          Enterprise environments have constraints that lab environments don't: change approval
          processes, compliance requirements, integration dependencies, legacy systems that can't
          be replaced and SLAs that mean something. Working within those constraints for over a
          decade changes how you evaluate technical decisions.
        </p>
        <p>
          In 24x7 critical environments, you learn that the cost of a wrong decision compounds
          over time. A poorly designed network segment is easy to overlook in development — it
          becomes a significant refactor when workloads are running in production and teams are
          building on top of it. The same applies to IAM design, monitoring gaps and undocumented
          infrastructure.
        </p>
        <p>
          That experience translates into specific habits: always design with the operational
          phase in mind, not just the delivery phase. Think about who will need to troubleshoot
          this at 2am. Consider what happens when the person who built it is no longer available.
          Design for change, not for the current snapshot.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-10 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
        {[
          {
            label: '10+',
            desc:  'Years in enterprise environments',
            color: 'text-blue-400',
          },
          {
            label: '5',
            desc:  'Active Azure and cloud certifications',
            color: 'text-violet-400',
          },
          {
            label: '24×7',
            desc:  'Critical production operations experience',
            color: 'text-slate-300',
          },
        ].map(({ label, desc, color }) => (
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-800 p-6 text-center" style="background-color: #0d1424;">
            <p class={`text-3xl font-bold ${color}`}>{label}</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">{desc}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Focus areas ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="border-b border-slate-800 py-20" style="background-color: #080d1a;">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <span class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-blue-400">
        Focus
      </span>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold text-white sm:text-3xl">
        What I focus on
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
        Four areas where I spend most of my technical energy and where I have the most
        depth to contribute.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 space-y-8">

        <div class="flex gap-6">
          <span class="mt-1 font-mono text-xs font-bold text-blue-400 flex-shrink-0 w-6">01</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white">Azure platform engineering</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-400">
              Hub-spoke topology design, VNet and subnet architecture, NSG rule management,
              Private Endpoints, Azure Firewall policy hierarchies, Azure Bastion, DNS zones
              and resolution across peered networks. The networking layer is where most
              enterprise Azure complexity lives — and where getting it wrong is most costly.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex gap-6">
          <span class="mt-1 font-mono text-xs font-bold text-violet-400 flex-shrink-0 w-6">02</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white">Terraform and Infrastructure as Code</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-400">
              Module design, remote state with Azure Blob, workspace strategy, variable management,
              provider version pinning and CI/CD integration. Writing Terraform that other engineers
              can read, extend and operate — not just Terraform that works once.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex gap-6">
          <span class="mt-1 font-mono text-xs font-bold text-cyan-400 flex-shrink-0 w-6">03</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white">DevOps and CI/CD</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-400">
              Azure DevOps pipeline design, GitHub Actions workflows, service connections and
              OIDC-based keyless authentication, environment gating, pipeline-as-code patterns.
              Integration of infrastructure deployment pipelines with application delivery pipelines
              — including Azure Data Factory and database deployments.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex gap-6">
          <span class="mt-1 font-mono text-xs font-bold text-slate-400 flex-shrink-0 w-6">04</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white">Reliability and operations</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-7 text-slate-400">
              Monitoring and alerting design with Azure Monitor and Log Analytics, NSG flow logs,
              diagnostic settings baseline, RBAC and access governance, incident response process
              and runbook culture. Operational practices built over years in environments where
              downtime has direct business impact.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Direction ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="border-b border-slate-800 py-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <span class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-blue-400">
        Direction
      </span>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-bold text-white sm:text-3xl">
        Where I'm heading
      </h2>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-base leading-8 text-slate-400">
        <p>
          The natural progression from platform engineering is cloud architecture — moving
          from implementing designs to owning them. The AZ-305 (Azure Solutions Architect Expert)
          certification reflects that direction: not a credential collected for its own sake,
          but validation of a shift in how I engage with technical problems.
        </p>
        <p>
          The difference between an engineer who builds what's specified and an architect who
          defines what should be built is largely about breadth of context: understanding
          cost implications, organisational constraints, long-term maintainability and
          cross-service integration patterns. That's the gap I'm actively closing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Specifically, I'm deepening work in three areas: enterprise-scale Azure landing zone
          design, advanced networking (multi-region, BGP, ExpressRoute integration) and
          platform engineering at scale — building internal developer platforms that abstract
          infrastructure complexity without hiding it completely from the teams that need
          to understand it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-10 flex flex-wrap gap-2">
        {[
          'Cloud Architecture',
          'Azure Landing Zones',
          'Enterprise Networking',
          'Platform Engineering',
          'Internal Developer Platforms',
        ].map((tag) => (
          <span
            class="rounded-md border border-blue-800/50 px-3 py-1.5 text-sm text-blue-300/80"
            style="background-color: rgba(30,58,138,0.12);"
          >
            {tag}
          </span>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTASection />
</BaseLayout>
